{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17501032","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17501032"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:22:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:22:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1712"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1712","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1712"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.21,0.25,0.07,0.11,0.35]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1712"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51322"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1712","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1712"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1712"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36611"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"682"},{"type":"tags","id":"701"},{"type":"tags","id":"1268"},{"type":"tags","id":"2167"},{"type":"tags","id":"4951"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3322"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3334"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5710"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14225"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42375"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44518"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51322","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/51322"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old man is brought into the Emergency Department after a domestic incident during which he was stabbed with a kitchen knife. On examination, he is fully conscious, alert and oriented. His pulse rate is 75/min, blood pressure 120/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 15/min and SpO2 96% on room air. The abdominal findings are shown (Image). There is tenderness around the stab site, extending into the epigastrium and left upper quadrant. A FAST scan is performed and does not reveal any findings of significance.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Wound debridement","Reduction of protruding fat","Absorbent dressing","Vacuum-assisted dressing","Laparotomy"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA significant part of the greater omentum is on display in this image. The abdominal findings of localised tenderness suggests peritoneal irritation. This could be due to perforation of an underlying structure (stomach, small bowel) with leakage of gut contents. Depending on the volume of free intraperitoneal fluid, the sensitivity of a FAST scan will vary. There would need to be at least 150 ml of free fluid for a reliable interpretation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical findings, together with the nature and site of the injury means that the underlying region must be explored, hence expediting the need for a \u003Cstrong\u003Elaparotomy\u003C/strong\u003E. Liver injury, perforation of the stomach and damage to the diaphragm would be likely consequences of such an attack. Even if the imaging studies were done and did not find anything, this patient will need the wound explored.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe real world management of this patient may well vary between centres. It has been a bone of contention for years in major and high volume trauma centres of what to do with isolated omental evisceration. The views vary between continued observation and formal surgical exploration. With the former approach there is a risk of missing a deeper injury. Essentially the availability of excellent quality CT scanning and serial clinical evaluation can select some of these isolated omental eviscerations for best management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbsorbent dressings\u003C/strong\u003E are primarily useful in wounds with significant amounts of exudate, and would be unhelpful in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVacuum-assisted dressings\u003C/strong\u003E are useful in cavitating wounds with significant amounts of debris and oedema, as they help promote angiogenesis and granulation tissue formation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf this patient was to be managed without operative intervention, then the protruding omentum would have to be dealt with - ideally by local excision and \u003Cstrong\u003Ewound debridement\u003C/strong\u003E. There would be no place for pushing the (contaminated) \u003Cstrong\u003Eprotruding tissue\u003C/strong\u003E back into the peritoneal cavity.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Suspected omental injury with associated peritonitis should be managed with a laparotomy to look for intra-abdominal organ damage."],"references":["Y\u00fccel M, \u00d6zpek A, Y\u00fcksekda\u011f S, Kabak \u0130, Ba\u015fak F, K\u0131l\u0131\u00e7 A, et al. The management of penetrating abdominal stab wounds with organ or omentum evisceration: The results of a clinical trial. Ulus Cerrahi Derg. 2014;30(4):207. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4379793/","Kong VY, Weale RD, Blodgett JM, Madsen A, Laing GL, Clarke DL. Selective Nonoperative Management of Abdominal Stab Wounds with Isolated Omental Evisceration is Safe: A South African Experience. Scand J Surg. 2021;110(2):214-221. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32090686/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36611"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1712"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15513"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15513","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15513"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/995d8c96-0343-43fb-9eb9-2bff20146727.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/995d8c96-0343-43fb-9eb9-2bff20146727.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36611","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/36611"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-23T22:54:19+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-23T22:56:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1712"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51322"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/a